in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Threonine\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"The network targets threonine as the final product of a connected prebiotic graph centered on cyanide/nitrile chemistry, aldehyde chemistry, and sugar-derived beta-hydroxy precursors, while explicitly incorporating hydrothermal routes mainly as upstream feedstock generation and stability constraints rather than productive threonine synthesis. The most literature-grounded direct threonine-positive branches are the aminomalononitrile (AMN) plus electrophile plus hydrolysis route and spark-discharge precursor generation followed by aqueous trapping/hydrolysis. Additional connected pathways represent the literature-supported but weaker Strecker 2-hydroxybutanal branch, glycine plus acetaldehyde aldol/beta-hydroxy chemistry, and threose-derived surface chemistry. Hydrothermal nodes supply formate, acetaldehyde, and carbonyl feedstocks to surface networks, while hydrothermal destruction reactions constrain where threonine accumulates. Ten pathways are enumerated as distinct route variants through the same connected bipartite network.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"metha