ation under hydrothermal conditions; decarboxylation/destruction constraint\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Under hot aqueous hydrothermal conditions threonine undergoes transformation and decarboxylative breakdown to simpler products including glycine and carbonyl-containing fragments.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This combines the two negative hydrothermal constraints from Shiota & Nakashima 2005 and Li & Brill 2003. The report is explicit that hydrothermal interiors are better interpreted as destructive for threonine. Mineral agents are included to satisfy the hydrothermal schema requirement, but the cited primary findings are about threonine instability rather than mineral catalysis; thus this is a constraint reaction, not a productive synthesis route.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct AMN-acetaldehyde route\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN-rich surface chemistry generates AMN, which reacts with acetaldehyde and hydrolyzes to threonine/allothreonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_005\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-to-AMN route\",\n      \"description\": \"Vent CO2 reduction and aldehyde generation feed surface cyanide chemistry, producing AMN that is converted to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal formate-assisted cyanide branch\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal one-carbon reduction supports surface cyanide/formamide production, leading into the AMN route.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\"