n": 0.7, "target_achievement": 0.45, "overall_confidence": 0.46, "feedback": "Threose formation from formaldehyde via formose-type chemistry is plausible with borate stabilization, but the conversion of threose plus ammonia directly to threonine is poorly specified and not directly supported in the literature. The research explicitly notes that the sugar-derived branch is only supported at the precursor level, not as a demonstrated threonine synthesis.", "approved": false, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_010"], "suggestions": ["Break rxn_010 into explicit amination and redox steps with realistic intermediates.", "Treat the sugar branch as precursor-supporting rather than target-achieving.", "Add stronger justification for nitrogen incorporation and carbon skeleton retention."]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_002": 0.62, "rxn_005": 0.76, "rxn_010": 0.28}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.5, "pathway_coherence": 0.68, "environmental_progression": 0.86, "target_achievement": 0.45, "overall_confidence": 0.52, "feedback": "This pathway scores well for environmental integration from hydrothermal carbonyl generation to surface sugar chemistry, but it fails in the final target-forming step. The threose-to-threonine conversion is too speculative, so despite good network storytelling it is not a strong synthesis route to the target.", "approved": false, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_010", "rxn_002"], "suggestions": ["Retain this as an environmental precursor pathway rather than a validated threonine pathway.", "Replace rxn_010 with a literature-supported target-forming step if possible.", "Clarify hydrothermal product distribution and mineral catalysis in rxn_002."]}], "best_pathway_id": "P1", "overall_confidence": 0.72, "network_feedback": "The network is topologically decent and chemically mixed. Strengths include a connected graph, multiple convergent branches, reasonable hub usage around acetaldehyde, HCN, AMN, glycine, and threose, and good recognition that hydrothermal settings are more relevant as feedstock sources and destruction constraints than as productive threonine environments. The direct AMN branch and the spark-discharge branch align best with the supplied literature and do produce the target. However, overall approval is limited by several major issues: multiple reactions compress multistep chemistry into implausible one-step conversions; the key surface reaction generating HCN/formamide from formaldehyde plus ammonia is weakly justified; the sugar-derived and glycine-aldol target-forming steps are speculative; the Strecker 2-hydroxybutanal branch lacks explicit precursor provenance; and literature alignment is incomplete because the network summary omits per-reaction citations and exact conditions. Environmental interconnection is present, but mineral-agent specification appears missing from the presented reaction summaries despite being a required design constraint. As a complete synthesis network, it is acceptable as a hypothesis-generating map but not strong enough for approval at the >=0.9 threshold.", "hub_quality": 0.83, "convergence_quality": 0.8}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 43430.19509315491, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-06-14T20:19:15.484836", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: Threonine\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nThe following deep research report contains peer-reviewed literature on prebiotic synthesis\nof Threonine. Your network design MUST be based on these findings.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n# Prebiotic Synthesis Report: Threonine\n\n## 1. Executive summary\nThis report is restricted to validated/analysed workspace content from the available s5/s6 upstream artifacts and their cited source lists. No uncited claims are introduced.\n\nAcross the retained threonine network, the strongest **direct positive experimental support** for abiotic threonine formation is the **aminomalononitrile (AMN) + electrophile(s) + hydrolysis** route, for which the gathered source notes state that **DL-threonine and allo-threonine were identified and quantitated** in Thanassi\u2019s *Journal of Molecular Evolution* paper, although the numeric yields themselves were **not recoverable** in the available workspace because primary-source extraction failed (Thanassi 1975, *Journal of Molecular Evolution*; exact locator carried upstream as: \u201csource access unavailable; prior paperAnalyzer attempt on PMID:2786 failed and no SI was retrieved\u201d). A second direct positive route is **spark-discharge / Miller-Urey chemistry**, where Ring et al. reported **threonine and allothreonine** among discharge products, again without recoverable numeric yield in the validated workspace (Ring et al. 1972, *PNAS*; exact locator carried upstream as: \u201csource access unavailable; no full text or SI retrieved in available tooling/workspace\u201d).\n\nOther synthesis branches remain more weakly supported. A **2-hydroxybutanal Strecker** route is chemically well motivated by general Strecker logic and by threonine/allothreonine precedent, but the gathered set did **not** retrieve a threonine-specific primary experiment directly demonstrating that exact substrate combination under prebiotic conditions. Likewise, a **glycine + acetaldehyde aldol / beta-hydroxy** route and a **sugar-derived threose branch** remain plausible but under-demonstrated in the retained evidence.\n\nThe hydrothermal literature in the retained set is more useful as a **constraint** than as a synthesis route. Threonine is reported to transform under hydrothermal conditions at **121\u2013160 \u00b0C** (Shiota & Nakashima 2005, *Chemistry Letters*) and to undergo decarboxylation in water at **270\u2013340 \u00b0C and 275 bar** (Li & Brill 2003, *Journal of Physical Chemistry A*). In the validated network these hydrothermal entries are therefore retained as upstream routes but interpreted primarily as **destruction/transformation**, not productive synthesis.\n\nAcross abiotic routes, the retained evidence consistently supports **mixtures involving threonine and allothreonine**, rather than selective formation of a single stereoisomer. No validated upstream artifact provided a recoverable numeric **threo/allo ratio**.\n\nA major unresolved gap is quantitative: the final yield artifact explicitly documents that **no verified numeric threonine yield was recovered for any retained route** using the available workspace and source-access tooling. Therefore, the ranked route table below contains **no yield-backed numeric rows**; all routes are retained and explicitly marked as **yield not recoverable / not reported in available validated extraction**.\n\n## 2. Ranked route table\n**Ranking rule required by task:** yield-backed routes first, flagged. **Result from validated upstream artifacts:** no retained route has a recoverable numeric yield. Therefore, there are **0 yield-backed routes** and all retained routes appear below as non-yield rows, with yield fields carried unaltered from upstream.\n\n| Rank group | Route ID | Yield-backed flag | Route name | Precursors | Route type | T | P | pH | Catalyst / agents | Phase / medium | Environment | Threo/allo selectivity | Yield | Citation | Exact locator |\n|---|---:|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Non-yield | R1 | NO | Strecker / 2-hydroxybutanal | 2-hydroxybutanal + NH3 + HCN + H2O | Strecker / 2-hydroxybutanal | not reported / not recovered | not reported / not recovered | pH-sensitive carbonyl/imine/aminonitrile equilibria; exact numeric pH not extracted | NH3, CN- / HCN | aqueous; hydrolysis workup required | cyanide-bearing surface waters / evaporative ponds | mixed threo/allo predicted; no direct measured ratio retrieved | yield/data not recoverable - source access unavailable (source: R1; reference: threonine_hypotheses.md citing Magrino et al. 2021 J Phys Chem Lett and Strecker-related source-list entries) | threonine_hypotheses.md citing Magrino et al. 2021 J Phys Chem Lett and Strecker-related source-list entries | source access unavailable; no threonine-specific primary full text/SI opened in available tooling/workspace |\n| Non-yield | R2 | NO | cyanide / aminomalononitrile route | aminomalononitrile + electrophile(s) + H2O (hydrolysis) | cyanide / aminomalononitrile route | mild conditions reported qualitatively | not reported / not recovered | not reported / not recovered | AMN; electrophilic carbonyl partner(s); hydrolysis reagents not extracted | aqueous, followed by hydrolysis | HCN-rich concentration settings; drying/wetting plausible | both DL-threonine and allo-threonine reported | yield/data not recoverable - source access unavailable (source: PMID:2786 / Thanassi 1975 Journal of Molecular Evolution) | Thanassi 1975 Journal of Molecular Evolution (PMID:2786) | source access unavailable; prior paperAnalyzer attempt on PMID:2786 failed and no SI was retrieved |\n| Non-yield | R3 | NO | spark-discharge / Miller-Urey | CH4 + N2 + H2O + NH3 (reducing atmosphere gases; some variants +/- H2S) with electric discharge | spark-discharge / Miller-Urey | not reported / not recovered | not reported / not recovered | aqueous trapping/hydrolysis used downstream; exact pH not extracted | electric discharge energy input | gas phase discharge with aqueous trap / hydrolysis | lightning-driven reducing atmosphere; volcanic plume microenvironments | threonine and allothreonine both reported; no enantioselective bias reported | yield/data not recoverable - source access unavailable (source: Ring et al. 1972 PNAS) | Ring et al. 1972 PNAS | source access unavailable; no full text or SI retrieved in available tooling/workspace |\n| Non-yield | R4 | NO | aldol / beta-hydroxy route | glycine + acetaldehyde | aldol / beta-hydroxy route | not reported / not recovered | not reported / not recovered | pH likely controls glycinate/enolate/iminium accessibility; numeric values not extracted | possible mineral/Lewis-acid assistance discussed in route logic; none directly established for threonine-specific prebiotic experiment | aqueous, possibly drying/eutectic concentration variants | shallow ponds / wet-dry shorelines | likely threo/allo mixture if route operates; no direct measured ratio retrieved | yield/data not recoverable - source access unavailable (source: R4 / Subbaraman et al. 1972 route context) | Subbaraman et al. 1972; threonine_aldol_sugar_sources.json; threonine_hypotheses.md | source access unavailable; no primary full text/SI opened for a threonine-specific source in available tooling/workspace |\n| Non-yield | R5 | NO | sugar-derived beta-hydroxy route | threose or related tetrose + ammonia/amine donor + redox/amination chemistry | sugar-derived beta-hydroxy route | not reported / not recovered | not reported / not recovered | sugar availability and stability pH-sensitive; numeric values not extracted | possible mineral/borate/redox assistance depending mechanism | evaporative or cyclic surface aqueous systems | surface pools with sugar formation/concentration | not reported for threonine outcome in gathered sources | yield/data not recoverable - source access unavailable (source: R5 / sugar-derived route context) | 2012 JACS threose/erythrose precursor literature as cited in threonine_hypotheses.md; threonine_aldol_sugar_sources.json | source access unavailable; no direct threonine-yield primary full text/SI opened in available tooling/workspace |\n| Non-yield | R6 | NO | hydrothermal transformation / degradation | threonine (aqueous solution) | hydrothermal transformation / degradation | 121-160 | hydrothermal (not numerically extracted) | not reported / not recovered | none specified in source-list note | aqueous hydrothermal solution | hydrothermal systems / hot aqueous settings | not central / not reported | yield/data not recoverable - source access unavailable (source: Shiota & Nakashima 2005 Chemistry Letters) | Shiota & Nakashima 2005 Chemistry Letters | source access unavailable; no primary full text or SI retrieved in available tooling/workspace |\n| Non-yield | R7 | NO | hydrothermal decarboxylation / destruction | threonine in water | hydrothermal decarboxylation / destruction | 270-340 | 275 bar | not reported / not recovered | none specified in source-list note | aqueous hydrothermal flow conditions | deep hydrothermal / superheated water | not central / not reported | yield/data not recoverable - source access unavailable (source: Li & Brill 2003 Journal of Physical Chemistry A) | Li & Brill 2003 Journal of Physical Chemistry A | source access unavailable; prior PDF fetch timed out and no SI was retrieved in available tooling/workspace |\n\n## 3. Per-route narrative\n\n### R1. Strecker / 2-hydroxybutanal\nThe retained network treats this as a chemically plausible Strecker route from **2-hydroxybutanal + NH3 + HCN + H2O** through an **imine / aminonitrile** intermediate to **DL-threonine + DL-allothreonine** after hydrolysis. The route is grounded in general Strecker chemistry and in the mechanistic framing of Magrino, Pietrucci, and Saitta (2021, *Journal of Physical Chemistry Letters*), plus Strecker stereochemistry analogues retrieved in the source list. However, the validated upstream summary is explicit that **no direct threonine-specific experimental paper for this exact substrate combination was retrieved**. Accordingly, temperature, pressure, time, concentration, and numeric yield remain unrecovered, and the threo/allo outcome is only a **prediction** (\u201cmixed threo/allo predicted; no direct measured ratio retrieved\u201d). This route should therefore be treated as a **supported hypothesis**, not a demonstrated threonine synthesis in the retained evidence.\n\n### R2. Cyanide / aminomalononitrile route\nThis is the strongest direct threonine-positive route in the retained network. The source notes for **Thanassi 1975, *Journal of Molecular Evolution*** state that reactions of **aminomalononitrile (AMN) with electrophiles**, followed by hydrolysis, yielded amino acids including **DL-threonine and allo-threonine**, and that these products were **identified and quantitated**. The validated route table preserves only qualitative conditions: **mild conditions reported qualitatively**, aqueous medium, hydrolysis step, and an HCN-rich setting as the environmental analogue. Crucially, the primary paper could not be extracted in the workspace, so the exact electrophile set, hydrolysis protocol, numeric yields, and any diastereomeric ratios remain unavailable. Even so, among retained routes this is the clearest case of **direct experimental abiotic threonine formation**.\n\n### R3. Spark-discharge / Miller-Urey\nThe retained evidence identifies **Ring, Wolman, Friedmann, and Miller (1972, *PNAS*)** as the core source reporting **threonine and allothreonine** among products from electric-discharge experiments using reduced gases such as **CH4, N2, H2O, and traces of NH3**. The route is represented as gas-phase discharge with aqueous trapping/hydrolysis, relevant to lightning-driven reducing atmospheres or volcanic plume microenvironments. No numeric yield, pressure, or exact pH was recovered in the validated artifacts. Later reanalysis and review sources in the retained set (Johnson et al. 2008, Parker et al. 2011, Bada 2013) broaden the discharge context but do not, in the validated summaries, supply a recoverable threonine yield. Thus the route is directly supported for **presence**, but not quantitatively constrained here.\n\n### R4. Aldol / beta-hydroxy route\nThis route links **glycine + acetaldehyde** to threonine-type beta-hydroxy amino acids. The core prebiotic source retained for this branch is **Subbaraman, Kazi, and Choughuley (1972, *Indian Journal of Biochemistry and Biophysics*)**, titled *Reactions of aldehydes with glycine as possible prebiotic events*. The validated network keeps the route because it is chemically relevant and historically proposed, but it also marks the evidence as weak: no direct threonine-specific prebiotic experiment with extracted conditions or yields was available in the workspace. Mechanistic support comes mainly from non-prebiotic threonine-aldolase literature showing that **glycine + aldehyde \u21cc beta-hydroxy-alpha-amino acid** chemistry is feasible, but those are analogues rather than direct prebiotic demonstrations. In the retained evidence, this route remains **plausible but under-demonstrated**.\n\n### R5. Sugar-derived beta-hydroxy route\nThe sugar-derived branch starts from **threose or related tetroses**, then invokes amination/redox chemistry to reach threonine. The retained evidence supports the **availability of threose** under simple prebiotic conditions via the 2012 *JACS* paper on enantioselective generation of **erythrose and threose**, but does **not** provide a direct threonine-from-threose experiment. The route is therefore explicitly retained as an **inferred precursor-to-target link only**. No threo/allo selectivity, yield, or detailed conditions were recovered for threonine formation itself.\n\n### R6. Hydrothermal transformation / degradation\nThis route is included because it appears in the upstream network, but it is not a productive synthesis route. **Shiota and Nakashima (2005, *Chemistry Letters*)** are summarized as showing that threonine in aqueous solution transforms under hydrothermal conditions at **121\u2013160 \u00b0C**, producing **glycine plus other products including peptides/polymers**. The retained evidence therefore uses this route mainly as a **stability constraint**: threonine can be transformed in hot aqueous systems rather than preserved.\n\n### R7. Hydrothermal decarboxylation / destruction\nSimilarly, **Li and Brill (2003, *Journal of Physical Chemistry A*)** provide direct evidence for threonine destruction in water at **270\u2013340 \u00b0C and 275 bar**. The validated route table preserves these quantitative T/P values but no kinetic constants, because the PDF fetch failed upstream. This route strongly supports the conclusion that **deep, hot hydrothermal conditions are hostile to threonine persistence**.\n\n## 4. Intermediates and precursors\nThe retained precursor/intermediate network identifies the following species as central to threonine-related prebiotic chemistry:\n\n- **2-hydroxybutanal**: proposed aldehyde precursor for the Strecker branch leading to threonine/allothreonine.\n- **NH3 and HCN / CN-**: core Strecker reagents in the hydroxybutanal route.\n- **Imine / aminonitrile (threonine aminonitrile) [inferred]**: key intermediate in the Strecker branch; retained as inferred rather than directly observed in a threonine-specific prebiotic experiment.\n- **Aminomalononitrile (AMN)**: central nitrile precursor in the strongest direct threonine-positive route; reacts with electrophiles and then hydrolyzes to amino acids including threonine/allothreonine.\n- **Electrophilic carbonyl partners**: required in the AMN route, though the exact set was not extracted in the validated workspace.\n- **Glycine**: both a precursor in the aldol route and a product of hydrothermal threonine transformation.\n- **Acetaldehyde**: key carbonyl precursor in the aldol / beta-hydroxy route; its primordial availability is supported in the retained source list by the 2023 *Life* review on acetaldehyde formation/stabilization.\n- **Threose / related tetroses**: upstream sugar precursors in the sugar-derived branch; supported as plausible prebiotic sugars but not directly linked experimentally to threonine in the retained evidence.\n- **Complex discharge condensate / precursor pool**: intermediate product mixture in spark-discharge experiments before hydrolysis and amino-acid analysis.\n\nOverall, the retained network supports two broad precursor regimes: **cyanide/nitrile chemistry** (Strecker, AMN) and **carbonyl/sugar chemistry** (acetaldehyde, threose), with the former better supported experimentally for threonine itself.\n\n## 5. Mineral catalysts and surfaces\nNo retained route demonstrates a **threonine-specific mineral-catalyzed synthesis** with extracted conditions and yield. The mineral/surface evidence in the validated source set is therefore contextual rather than route-defining.\n\nRelevant retained mineral/surface themes are:\n\n- **Pyrite / FeS2 and chiral mineral surfaces**: retained as stereochemical analogues for amino-acid formation or chiral induction, including the 2024 *Nature Communications* paper on prebiotic formation of enantiomeric excess D-amino acids on natural pyrite. In the validated threonine network this supports only the possibility that mineral surfaces could influence stereochemistry; it does **not** directly demonstrate threonine synthesis.\n- **Montmorillonite / clays**: retained sources include broad reviews and adsorption studies, plus dissertation-level evidence that **L-threonine was among amino acids tested for adsorption to montmorillonite** under varying pH and salts. This supports concentration/selective adsorption scenarios, not direct threonine formation.\n- **Goethite / ferrihydrite / iron oxyhydroxides**: retained as relevant adsorption and vent-mineral contexts. The 2019 *PNAS* iron oxyhydroxide chimney analogue study is important for amino-acid synthesis under redox/pH gradients, but in the validated summary it reports **alanine**, not threonine.\n- **Possible borate/mineral assistance in sugar stabilization**: retained only as a mechanistic possibility in the sugar-derived branch; no threonine-specific demonstration was recovered.\n\nThus, mineral evidence in the retained set supports three roles: **adsorption/concentration**, **possible stereochemical bias**, and **environmental plausibility of reactive interfaces**. It does not yet support a validated threonine-specific mineral-catalyzed synthesis route.\n\n## 6. Experimental evidence and environmental context\n### Direct experimental evidence for threonine formation\n- **AMN/electrophile route**: direct experimental support for abiotic threonine and allothreonine formation (Thanassi 1975, *Journal of Molecular Evolution*), though numeric yields and exact conditions were not recoverable.\n- **Spark-discharge route**: direct experimental support for threonine and allothreonine occurrence in discharge products (Ring et al. 1972, *PNAS*), again without recoverable numeric yield in the validated workspace.\n\n### Indirect or inferential synthesis evidence\n- **2-hydroxybutanal Strecker**: mechanistically plausible, but not directly demonstrated in the retained threonine-specific evidence.\n- **Glycine + acetaldehyde aldol**: historically proposed and chemically plausible, but weakly evidenced for threonine specifically.\n- **Threose-derived route**: supported only at the precursor level.\n\n### Negative or constraining evidence\n- **Hydrothermal systems**: direct evidence shows threonine transformation/destruction at elevated temperature. This makes hot hydrothermal cores poor candidates for net threonine accumulation.\n- **Ice/UV photochemistry**: foundational UV-ice studies are retained, but the validated summaries do not establish a secure threonine-positive result. These environments are therefore better treated as possible **precursor** sources than as demonstrated threonine sources.\n- **Meteorites / extraterrestrial delivery**: retained meteoritic sources explicitly note either **absence of threonine** in analyzed Murchison material or only **minor traces** considered likely terrestrial contamination (Engel & Nagy 1982, *Nature*; related 1982 *Nature* correspondence). This is a strong constraint on claims of abundant indigenous meteoritic threonine.\n\n### Environmental interpretation\nThe retained evidence most strongly favors **surface or near-surface aqueous settings** where cyanide chemistry, aldehydes, and concentration cycles can operate:\n- **cyanide-bearing surface waters / evaporative ponds** for Strecker and AMN chemistry;\n- **lightning-driven reducing atmospheres / volcanic plume microenvironments** for spark-discharge production;\n- **shallow ponds / wet-dry shorelines** for glycine\u2013aldehyde chemistry;\n- **surface pools with sugar formation/concentration** for the threose branch.\n\nBy contrast, **hot hydrothermal interiors** are disfavored as net threonine reservoirs because the retained evidence emphasizes degradation rather than synthesis/preservation.\n\n## 7. Open questions and debates\n1. **Where are the numeric yields?**  \n   The largest unresolved gap is quantitative. The final validated yield artifact states that no verified numeric threonine yield could be recovered for any retained route using the available workspace and source-access tooling.\n\n2. **How strong is the 2-hydroxybutanal Strecker route specifically?**  \n   General Strecker chemistry is strong, but the retained evidence lacks a direct threonine-specific experiment for this exact aldehyde.\n\n3. **What exact electrophiles and conditions were used in the AMN route?**  \n   Thanassi\u2019s paper is clearly important, but the validated workspace could not extract the exact reaction details or numeric yields.\n\n4. **What are the actual threo/allo ratios in abiotic products?**  \n   Multiple routes report both threonine and allothreonine, but no validated upstream artifact recovered a numeric diastereomer ratio.\n\n5. **Can mineral surfaces do more than adsorb?**  \n   The retained evidence supports adsorption and possible stereochemical influence, but not threonine-specific catalytic formation.\n\n6. **Are ice photochemistry and meteorites meaningful threonine sources?**  \n   In the retained evidence, these are at best indirect precursor or delivery contexts. Positive threonine claims remain weak relative to explicit absence/contamination concerns.\n\n7. **Can cooler hydrothermal margins preserve threonine?**  \n   The retained evidence strongly disfavors hot cores, but leaves open whether cooler, rapidly quenched, or mineral-buffered microenvironments could preserve small amounts.\n\n## Coverage and source accounting\nBecause the s6 consolidation task failed upstream, the counts below are assembled directly from the validated s5/s6-available source-list artifacts and route artifacts in the workspace, without introducing external sources.\n\n- **Number of search angles represented:** 8  \n  1. General prebiotic/abiotic threonine  \n  2. Miller-Urey / spark discharge  \n  3. Hydrothermal  \n  4. Strecker / 2-hydroxybutanal  \n  5. Aldol / sugar-derived beta-hydroxy  \n  6. Meteoritic / extraterrestrial  \n  7. Ice / UV photochemistry  \n  8. Mineral / metal catalysis\n- **Total sources touched (sum of angle tallies):** 1641\n- **Total rows retained (sum of angle tallies):** 474\n- **Deduplicated retained source count:** 39 core retained sources cited in this final report\n\n### Unresolved coverage gaps\n- No validated s6 master deduplicated source artifact was available because the upstream s6 task failed before producing outputs.\n- No recoverable numeric threonine yields were available for any retained route.\n- Exact locators for primary yield tables or stereochemical tables are unavailable for key direct sources because source access failed upstream.\n- Mineral-catalyzed threonine-specific synthesis remains unsupported in the retained evidence.\n\n### Complete deduplicated retained source list used in this report\n1. Magrino, T.; Pietrucci, F.; Saitta, A. M. 2021. *Journal of Physical Chemistry Letters*. Step by Step Strecker Amino Acid Synthesis from ab Initio Prebiotic Chemistry. DOI: 10.1021/acs.jpclett.1c00194. URL: https://hal.sorbonne-universite.fr/hal-03174777/document\n2. Thanassi, J. W. 1975. *Journal of Molecular Evolution*. Reactions of aminomalononitrile with electrophiles. PMID: 2786. URL: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/2786/\n3. Ring, D.; Wolman, Y.; Friedmann, N.; Miller, S. L. 1972. *Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America*. Prebiotic Synthesis of Hydrophobic and Protein Amino Acids. DOI: 10.1073/pnas.69.3.765. URL: https://doi.org/10.1073/pnas.69.3.765\n4. Johnson, A. P.; Cleaves, H. J.; Dworkin, J. P.; Glavin, D. P.; Lazcano, A.; Bada, J. L. 2008. *Science*. The Miller Volcanic Spark Discharge Experiment. URL: https://www.science.org/doi/pdf/10.1126/science.1161527\n5. Parker, E. T.; Cleaves, H. J.; Dworkin, J. P.; Glavin, D. P.; Callahan, M.; Aubrey, A.; Lazcano, A.; Bada, J. L. 2011. *Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America*. Primordial synthesis of amines and amino acids in a 1958 Miller H2S-rich spark discharge experiment. PMID: 21422282. URL: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21422282/\n6. Bada, J. L. 2013. *Chemical Society Reviews*. New insights into prebiotic chemistry from Stanley Miller's spark discharge experiments. URL: https://pubs.rsc.org/en/content/articlelanding/2013/cs/c3cs35433d\n7. Miller, S. L. 1974. *Origins