"Mineral-surface CO2 hydrogenation gives surface-bound reduced C1 species released as formate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Included as hydrothermal feedstock generation consistent with the system instructions for alkaline vent CO2 reduction on Fe-S minerals. This is used only as upstream carbon-source connectivity and not as a threonine-specific literature claim. The report emphasizes hydrothermal chemistry as more useful for constraints/upstream feedstocks than direct threonine synthesis (Aubrey et al., 2009; Amend & Shock, 1998).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type generation of formaldehyde and acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite/Fe0\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"subseafloor hydrothermal or vent-mixing context; anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO2/CO hydrogenation on iron oxide/metal surfaces produces reduced carbonyl compounds, including low-molecular-weight aldehydes.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Used to supply acetaldehyde and formaldehyde hubs needed by literature-retained carbonyl branches. Acetaldehyde availability under primordial conditions is explicitly supported contextually in the report, though not as a threonine-specific step (Life review 2023). This hydrothermal feedstock step is therefore a connecting reaction rather than a direct threonine synthesis claim (Life 2023 review as cited in the report; Aubrey et al., 2009).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface spark-discharge formation of methanimine and hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_016\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"not reported / not recovered\",\n        \"pressure\": \"not reported / not recovered\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"electric discharge energy; TiO2 and clay provide environmental surfaces for trapping/concentration\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"gas-phase discharge with aqueous trapping/hydrolysis in reducing atmosphere; lightning-driven microenvironment\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Electric discharge in reducing gas mixtures generates nitriles/imines that dissolve into aqueous traps.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Directly grounded in the retained spark-discharge route reporting threonine/allothreonine among products from reduced gases, with no recoverable exact T/P/pH in the validated workspace. Methanimine and HCN are canonical intermediates in Strecker-type discharge chemistry and are used here as explicit network connectors. Surface mineral agents are included to satisfy schema constraints as trapping/concentrating surfaces rather than claimed threonine-specific catalysts (Ring et al., 1972; Johnson et al., 2008; Parker et al., 2011; Bada, 2013).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface cyanide oligomerization to aminomalononitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2/montmorillonite as photochemical and concentrating surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"HCN-rich concentration settings; wet-dry concentration plausible; anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN-derived imine/nitrile condensation gives higher nitriles including aminomalononitrile under concentrated cyanide conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report identifies AMN as the central nitrile precursor in the strongest direct threonine-positive route. Exact AMN-formation conditions were not recovered from Thanassi, so this connecting step is necessary but should be treated as a network bridge grounded in general prebiotic cyanide oligomerization rather than a threonine-specific direct experiment (Thanassi, 1975; Magrino et al., 2021).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface aldol/formose branch to threose\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporative or cyclic surface pools; sugar stabilization by borate\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formose-type carbonyl homologation followed by borate stabilization yields tetroses including threose.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report retains threose as a supported precursor in the sugar-derived branch, but explicitly states that direct threose-to-threonine conversion is not experimentally demonstrated. This reaction is therefore limited to precursor generation only, consistent with the literature and prior feedback (2012 JACS threose/erythrose precursor literature as cited in the report).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface sugar-to-hydroxyaldehyde conversion to 2-hydroxybutanal\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"not reported / not recovered\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate/clay concentration surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporative pond or wet-dry shoreline; speculative connective step\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Carbonyl exchange/aldol-retroaldol style reorganization links tetrose-derived carbonyl chemistry and acetaldehyde feedstock to a beta-hydroxy aldehyde pool represented by 2-hydroxybutanal.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is a necessary connecting step to provide provenance for 2-hydroxybutanal, addressing prior feedback that the Strecker branch lacked explicit precursor origin. The report does not provide a directly demonstrated prebiotic threonine-specific experiment for this transformation, so this step is explicitly speculative but chemically motivated and kept only to connect the retained 2-hydroxybutanal Strecker hypothesis without inventing unsupported target-forming chemistry (Magrino et al., 2021; 2012 JACS threose/erythrose precursor literature; report section on R1 and R5).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface Strecker formation of threonine aminonitrile from 2-hydroxybutanal\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"not reported / not recovered\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral concentration surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"cyanide-bearing surface waters / evaporative ponds; pH-sensitive carbonyl-imine-aminonitrile equilibria\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldehyde condensation with ammonia gives an imine/iminium that is trapped by cyanide to form the aminonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This reaction follows the retained R1 route exactly in logic: 2-hydroxybutanal + NH3 + HCN to a threonine-type aminonitrile. The report is explicit that this branch is mechanistically plausible but not directly demonstrated in a threonine-specific primary experiment under recovered conditions, so it is included as a supported hypothesis rather than established direct synthesis (Magrino et al., 2021; report R1).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical/prebiotic hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile to threonine and allothreonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_016\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"variable; mild to moderate aqueous hydrolysis\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous hydrolysis workup; racemic/diastereomeric mixture expected\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nitrile hydrolysis proceeds through amide/carboxyl stages to the amino acid, preserving the beta-hydroxy amino acid skeleton as a diastereomeric mixture.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This completes the Strecker hypothesis branch retained in the report. The report predicts mixed threo/allo outcome and notes no recovered direct measured ratio. Hydrolysis of aminonitriles to amino acids is central to Strecker chemistry and is also part of the retained route description (Magrino et al., 2021; report R1).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical/prebiotic AMN plus electrophile(s) hydrolysis route to threonine and allothreonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_016\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"mild conditions reported qualitatively\",\n        \"pressure\": \"not reported / not recovered\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous reaction in HCN-rich concentration setting followed by hydrolysis; exact electrophile set not fully recovered\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"AMN reacts with electrophilic carbonyl partner(s) to build a substituted nitrile precursor that hydrolyzes to amino acids including threonine/allothreonine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the strongest direct threonine-positive route in the report. Thanassi's paper is summarized as showing that AMN with electrophiles followed by hydrolysis gave DL-threonine and allo-threonine, though exact yields and full experimental details were not recoverable. Acetaldehyde is used here as the explicit electrophilic carbonyl partner because the report identifies electrophilic carbonyl partners as required and acetaldehyde as a key primordial carbonyl precursor, but the exact electrophile assignment remains a necessary reconstruction and should be read cautiously (Thanassi, 1975; report R2; Life 2023 review as cited in report).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical/prebiotic spark-discharge precursor pool hydrolysis to glycine, threonine, and allothreonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_016\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"not reported / not recovered\",\n        \"pressure\": \"not reported / not recovered\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous trapping/hydrolysis downstream of electric discharge\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Complex nitrile/imino intermediates formed during discharge are hydrolyzed in aqueous workup to amino acids.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report directly supports threonine and allothreonine occurrence in spark-discharge products, but details of individual intermediate identities and exact yields are not recoverable. Representing the discharge products as a precursor pool and hydrolysis step is the least assumptive way to remain faithful to the literature while integrating the branch into the network (Ring et al., 1972; Johnson et al., 2008; Parker et al., 2011; Bada, 2013).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface glycine plus acetaldehyde beta-hydroxy route to threonine and allothreonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"not reported / not recovered\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"possible mineral concentration/Lewis-acid assistance\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"shallow ponds or wet-dry shorelines; speculative historical proposal\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldehyde addition to glycine-derived imine/enolate chemistry gives beta-hydroxy amino acid products as a diastereomeric mixture.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Included because the report retains this as the R4 aldol/beta-hydroxy route and identifies Subbaraman et al. as the key historical context, but also emphasizes that direct threonine-specific experimental support is weak. It is therefore included as a literature-retained plausible route, explicitly speculative and not compressed as the primary synthesis backbone (Subbaraman et al., 1972; Fesko, 2016; 2010 Applied Microbiology and Biotechnology review; report R4).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface electric-discharge precursor pool formation\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_016\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"not reported / not recovered\",\n        \"pressure\": \"not reported / not recovered\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"electric discharge energy; mineral surfaces for capture/concentration\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"reducing atmosphere with aqueous trap\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Spark discharge generates a chemically diverse reduced organic/nitrile condensate pool prior to hydrolysis and analysis.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This reaction explicitly captures the primary direct-discharge route as reported in the literature, separated from downstream hydrolysis for clearer topology and to support multiple target pathways. The validated report identifies presence of threonine/allothreonine in such discharge-derived mixtures, but not full mechanistic resolution or exact conditions (Ring et al., 1972; Johnson et al., 2008; Parker et al., 2011; Bada, 2013).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal transformation of threonine to glycine and other products\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_016\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_020\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"121-160C\",\n        \"pressure\": \"hydrothermal (not numerically extracted)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none specified in source; minerals denote hydrothermal interface context\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"hot aqueous hydrothermal conditions; transformation rather than net synthesis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Threonine undergoes hydrothermal transformation in water, producing glycine and additional products including condensation products.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report explicitly states that threonine transforms under hydrothermal conditions at 121-160 C and that this route is