Dworkin, J. P.; Sandford, S. A.; Cooper, G. W.; Allamandola, L. J. 2002. *Nature*. Racemic amino acids from the ultraviolet photolysis of interstellar ice analogues. URL: https://www.nature.com/articles/416401a\n24. Nuevo, M.; Meierhenrich, U. J.; d'Hendecourt, C.; Thiemann, W. H.-P.; Brack, A. 2008. *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*. A Detailed Study of the Amino Acids Produced from the Vacuum UV Irradiation of Interstellar Ice Analogs. URL: https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s11084-007-9117-y\n25. Elsila, J. E.; Dworkin, J. P.; Bernstein, M. P.; Sandford, S. A.; Allamandola, L. J. 2007. *Astrophysical Journal*. Mechanisms of Amino Acid Formation in Interstellar Ice Analogs. URL: https://science.gsfc.nasa.gov/content/uploadFiles/publication_files/Elsila_2007_ApJ_660_911.pdf\n26. Engel, M. H.; Nagy, B. 1982. *Nature*. Distribution and enantiomeric composition of amino acids in the Murchison meteorite. URL: https://www.nature.com/articles/296837a0.pdf\n27. 1982. *Nature / NASA NTRS record*. Distribution and enantiomeric composition of amino acids in the analyzed Murchison stone. URL: https://ntrs.nasa.gov/citations/19820048675\n28. 1983. *Nature correspondence*. On the reported optical activity of amino acids in the Murchison meteorite. URL: https://www.nature.com/articles/301496a0.pdf\n29. 2017. *Scientific Reports*. A new family of extraterrestrial amino acids in the Murchison meteorite. URL: https://www.nature.com/articles/s41598-017-00693-9\n30. 1994. *Origins of Life and Evolution of the Biosphere / ScienceDirect*. Characteristics and formation of amino acids and hydroxy acids of the Murchison meteorite. URL: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0273117799800684\n31. 2001. *Origins of Life and Evolution of the Biosphere*. Clays and other minerals in prebiotic processes. PMID: 11536583. URL: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11536583/\n32. 2024. *Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta*. Cation exchange to montmorillonite induces selective adsorption of amino acids. URL: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0016703724001029\n33. 2016. *Amino Acids*. The adsorption of amino acids and cations onto goethite: a prebiotic chemistry study. PMID: 26984319. DOI: 10.1007/s00726-016-2191-6. URL: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26984319/\n34. 2016. *Langmuir*. Adsorption of Lysine on Na-Montmorillonite and Competition with Cations. PMID: 27118104. DOI: 10.1021/acs.langmuir.6b00563. URL: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27118104/\n35. 1988. *Origins of Life and Evolution of the Biosphere*. The polymerization of amino acid adenylates on sodium-montmorillonite. PMID: 3237398. URL: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/3237398/\n36. 1976. *Origins of Life*. The mechanism of clay catalyzed polymerization of amino acid adenylates. PMID: 20183. URL: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20183/\n37. 2024. *Nature Communications*. Prebiotic formation of enantiomeric excess D-amino acids on natural pyrite by visible-light photocatalytic reductive amination of alpha-keto acids. PMID: 39578467. DOI: 10.1038/s41467-024-54481-x. URL: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/39578467/\n38. 2022. *Nature Chemistry*. Prebiotic synthesis of alpha-amino acids and orotate from alpha-ketoacids under plausible planetary conditions. URL: https://www.nature.com/articles/s41557-022-00999-w\n39. Aylward, N. 2019. *WSEAS Transactions on Biology and Medicine*. A Computational Study of a Prebiotic Synthesis of L-Threonine. URL: https://wseas.com/journals/bab/2019/a325108-087.pdf\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.72\n- Feedback: The network is topologically decent and chemically mixed. Strengths include a connected graph, multiple convergent branches, reasonable hub usage around acetaldehyde, HCN, AMN, glycine, and threose, and good recognition that hydrothermal settings are more relevant as feedstock sources and destruction constraints than as productive threonine environments. The direct AMN branch and the spark-discharge branch align best with the supplied literature and do produce the target. However, overall approval is limited by several major issues: multiple reactions compress multistep chemistry into implausible one-step conversions; the key surface reaction generating HCN/formamide from formaldehyde plus ammonia is weakly justified; the sugar-derived and glycine-aldol target-forming steps are speculative; the Strecker 2-hydroxybutanal branch lacks explicit precursor provenance; and literature alignment is incomplete because the network summary omits per-reaction citations and exact conditions. Environmental interconnection is present, but mineral-agent specification appears missing from the presented reaction summaries despite being a required design constraint. As a complete synthesis network, it is acceptable as a hypothesis-generating map but not strong enough for approval at the >=0.9 threshold.\n- Issues: ['This pathway has good cross-environment connectivity, but the chemistry is weakened by the speculative formaldehyde/ammonia to HCN+formamide step. Hydrothermal feedstock generation of acetaldehyde is plausible as upstream support, and the AMN branch remains strong once reached. However, the route to HCN is not literature-grounded in the supplied threonine report.', \"The hydrothermal formate node is reasonable, but the phrase 'formate-assisted cyanide branch' is not well realized chemically because formate is not clearly used to generate HCN in the given reactions. The branch depends on the same weak rxn_003 transformation, so literature alignment is limited despite good network connectivity.\", 'The Strecker logic is chemically sound in general, and hydrolysis of aminonitriles to amino acids is plausible. However, the literature report explicitly states that the 2-hydroxybutanal-to-threonine route is only a supported hypothesis, not directly demonstrated in the retained evidence. Additionally, 2-hydroxybutanal is not shown as being formed elsewhere in the network, which weakens route completeness.', 'This route benefits from using the shared cyanide hub, but it inherits two major weaknesses: speculative generation of HCN/formamide from formaldehyde and ammonia, and the under-demonstrated 2-hydroxybutanal Strecker step. It is topologically valid but only modestly supported chemically and by literature.', 'This is one of the weakest branches. The network treats glycine plus acetaldehyde as a one-step route to threonine/allothreonine, but the literature only supports this as a plausible historical proposal, not a validated direct prebiotic threonine synthesis. Mechanistically this likely requires multiple steps, activation, and poor selectivity, none of which are represented.', 'The first step is literature-supported at the mixture level, but the second step reuses the weak glycine-acetaldehyde direct threonine conversion. This makes the pathway topologically connected but chemically redundant and not well justified beyond speculative route extension.', 'Threose formation from formaldehyde via formose-type chemistry is plausible with borate stabilization, but the conversion of threose plus ammonia directly to threonine is poorly specified and not directly supported in the literature. The research explicitly notes that the sugar-derived branch is only supported at the precursor level, not as a demonstrated threonine synthesis.', 'This pathway scores well for environmental integration from hydrothermal carbonyl generation to surface sugar chemistry, but it fails in the final target-forming step. The threose-to-threonine conversion is too speculative, so despite good network storytelling it is not a strong synthesis route to the target.']\n\nAttempt 2:\n- Confidence: 0.82\n- Feedback: The network is topologically solid and connected, with sufficient molecule and reaction counts, identifiable hubs, multiple convergent branches, and clear Hydrothermal -> Surface -> Biochemical progression. It also does a good job incorporating the literature's key qualitative conclusion that threonine is best supported by AMN/electrophile hydrolysis chemistry and spark-discharge precursor pools, while hot hydrothermal settings act mainly as destructive constraints. The main limitations are chemical and literature-specific: several surface branches are overextended beyond the evidence, especially the formaldehyde-to-threose simplification, the threose-to-2-hydroxybutanal conversion, and the glycine + acetaldehyde direct route to threonine/allothreonine. Another issue is compliance with the original synthesis-network specification: Hydrothermal and Surface reactions were said to require explicit mineral agents, but the presented network summary omits them entirely, and the deep research findings themselves emphasize that threonine-specific mineral catalysis is not validated. Literature alignment is good for the AMN, spark-discharge, and hydrothermal degradation branches, moderate for the Strecker hypothesis branch, and weak for the aldol/sugar-derived constructive branches. Overall this is a credible but not approval-level network because it mixes strong literature-backed routes with several weakly supported bridging reactions.\n- Issues: ['Th