le hydrolysis).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical oxidative hydration/conversion of beta-hydroxy amino carbonyl intermediate to threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_016\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"variable\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mineral interface or pool chemistry; connector from under-demonstrated aldol branch\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"A reactive beta-hydroxy amino carbonyl intermediate converts to the stable amino acid product in aqueous prebiotic pools.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is another strictly necessary connector reflecting the report's statement that the glycine + acetaldehyde branch is plausible but mechanistically under-specified. Representing the unstable intermediate explicitly is more faithful than collapsing the route into a single unqualified step. This edge is therefore speculative but justified as a way to avoid the oversimplification criticized in prior attempts (Subbaraman et al., 1972; Fesko, 2016; report route R4).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal transformation of threonine to glycine and other products\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_016\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"121-160C\",\n        \"pressure\": \"hydrothermal\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"contextual mineral surfaces only\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"hot aqueous hydrothermal transformation; destructive constraint\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydrothermal transformation/decomposition of threonine produces glycine among other products including peptides/polymers.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This reaction encodes a key negative constraint from the report: threonine transforms under hydrothermal conditions and can yield glycine rather than persist. It is included to show Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface interconnection and to reflect that hot hydrothermal interiors are poor net threonine reservoirs (Shiota & Nakashima, 2005; report route R6).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal decarboxylative destruction of threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_016\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"270-340C\",\n        \"pressure\": \"275 bar\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"contextual hydrothermal mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"deep hydrothermal/superheated water; destructive decarboxylation constraint\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Thermal aqueous decarboxylation and fragmentation destroy threonine under superheated hydrothermal conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report preserves exact quantitative hydrothermal instability conditions from Li & Brill: 270-340 C and 275 bar. This is included as a destruction branch, not a productive synthesis route, and reinforces the literature conclusion that deep hot hydrothermal settings are hostile to threonine persistence (Li & Brill, 2003; report route R7).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct AMN-electrophile hydrolysis route\",\n      \"description\": \"Strongest direct literature-backed route: AMN reacts with electrophilic carbonyl partner and hydrolyzes to threonine/allothreonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_005\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal acetaldehyde feed into AMN route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal carbonyl generation supplies acetaldehyde to the direct AMN threonine pathway.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"2-hydroxybutanal Strecker to threonine\",\n      \"description\": \"Supported-hypothesis Strecker route from 2-hydroxybutanal via threonine aminonitrile and hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal carbonyl-supported Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal reduced-carbon feedstocks provide aldehydes that enter the hypothesized 2-hydroxybutanal Strecker branch.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker route via amide hydrolysis sequence\",\n      \"description\": \"Variant of the 2-hydroxybutanal Strecker branch passing through threoninamide before threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct spark-discharge threonine appearance\",\n      \"description\": \"Direct literature-backed discharge route where threonine/allothreonine occur in the complex product mixture after trapping/hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_020\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\