/C-C coupling within hydrothermal carbonyl synthesis networks yields small aldehydes.", "reasoning": "Used to provide acetaldehyde, a precursor explicitly identified in the report as central to the glycine + acetaldehyde and related carbonyl branches. The retained literature supports primordial availability of acetaldehyde and related aldehydes as plausible feedstocks, while not directly validating threonine formation in hydrothermal cores (Life review 2023 on acetaldehyde formation/stabilization; Aubrey et al., 2009)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Surface UV generation of formamide from HCN and water", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_016"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-exposed shallow surface waters"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical hydration/rearrangement of cyanide-derived species produces formamide in irradiated surface settings.", "reasoning": "Included only because the system specification lists UV photochemistry from HCN/H2O to formamide as a relevant surface reaction type. In the threonine literature set, UV/ice photochemistry is retained mainly as precursor chemistry rather than a secure direct threonine source, so this step is contextual and not target-defining (Mu\u00f1oz Caro et al., 2002; Bernstein et al., 2002; Nuevo et al., 2008)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Surface cyanide concentration to aminomalononitrile", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite/TiO2", "aqueous": "true", "other": "HCN-rich concentration setting, evaporative pond, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "HCN-rich oligomerization/concentration chemistry generates aminomalononitrile under surface pond conditions.", "reasoning": "AMN is explicitly identified by the report as the central precursor in the strongest direct threonine-positive route. Exact preparative details were not recoverable from the validated workspace, so this node-forming step is a necessary connection to represent the documented AMN regime. It remains a plausible HCN concentration step rather than a recovered exact protocol from Thanassi (Thanassi, 1975; Bada, 2013)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Surface formose/tetrose formation to threose", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporative pool with borate stabilization; wet-dry concentration cycles"}, "mechanism": "Formose-type carbonyl oligomerization with borate stabilization furnishes tetrose sugars including threose.", "reasoning": "The deep research report explicitly supports threose availability at the precursor level but not a direct threose-to-threonine synthesis. This step therefore captures the validated precursor branch only. Borate-assisted sugar stabilization is contextual, matching the report's discussion of possible mineral assistance in sugar chemistry (JACS 2012 tetrose precursor literature as cited in the report)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Surface conversion of acetaldehyde pool to 2-hydroxybutanal", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_019", "mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite/borate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "shallow ponds, wet-dry concentration, carbonyl-rich surface setting"}, "mechanism": "Carbonyl condensation and beta-hydroxylation within aldehyde pools generate hydroxy aldehydes including 2-hydroxybutanal.", "reasoning": "Th