nce >= 0.9\n\nOutput your evaluation as JSON matching the NetworkEvaluation schema.\n", "user_message": "Evaluate this synthesis network:\n\nTARGET MOLECULE: Threonine\nOVERALL STRATEGY: This network prioritizes the two strongest literature-supported direct abiotic threonine sources: (i) aminomalononitrile (AMN) reaction with electrophilic carbonyl partners followed by hydrolysis, and (ii) spark-discharge precursor pools yielding threonine/allothreonine after aqueous trapping and hydrolysis. Additional branches are included only where the report explicitly identifies them as plausible but under-demonstrated: a 2-hydroxybutanal Strecker route, a glycine + acetaldehyde beta-hydroxy route, and a sugar-derived threose branch. Hydrothermal chemistry is used mainly to supply simple reduced carbon feedstocks and to impose destruction constraints, consistent with the report that hot hydrothermal interiors are unfavorable for threonine preservation. Mineral agents are specified for every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction as required, but reasoning explicitly notes that threonine-specific mineral catalysis is generally contextual rather than directly validated in the literature.\n\nMOLECULES (20 nodes):\n  - mol_001: CO2 (carbon dioxide) [starting]\n  - mol_002: H2 (hydrogen) [starting]\n  - mol_003: CH2O2 (formic acid/formate) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_004: CH2O (formaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_005: C2H4O (acetaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_006: CH3NO (formamide) [intermediate]\n  - mol_007: CHN (HCN) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_008: CH5N (ammonia) [starting]\n  - mol_009: C2H4N2 (aminomalononitrile) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_010: C2H5NO2 (glycine) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_011: C4H8O2 (2-hydroxybutanal) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_012: C4H8N2O (threonine aminonitrile) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_013: C4H8O4 (threose) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_014: C4H9NO3 (threonine) [target]\n  - mol_015: C4H9NO3 (allothreonine) [intermediate]\n  - mol_016: H2O (wa