_015: mol_012, mol_016 -> mol_018 (Biochemical partial hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile to threoninamide) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_016: mol_017, mol_016 -> mol_014 (Biochemical oxidative hydration/conversion of beta-hydroxy amino carbonyl intermediate to threonine) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_017: mol_014, mol_016 -> mol_010 (Hydrothermal transformation of threonine to glycine and other products) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_018: mol_014, mol_016 -> mol_005, mol_001 (Hydrothermal decarboxylative destruction of threonine) [Hydrothermal]\n\nPATHWAYS (10):\n  - P1: Direct AMN-electrophile hydrolysis route (2 steps)\n  - P2: Hydrothermal acetaldehyde feed into AMN route (5 steps)\n  - P3: 2-hydroxybutanal Strecker to threonine (3 steps)\n  - P4: Hydrothermal carbonyl-supported Strecker route (6 steps)\n  - P5: Strecker route via amide hydrolysis sequence (4 steps)\n  - P6: Direct spark-discharge threonine appearance (1 steps)\n  - P7: Spark-discharge to cyanide then AMN route (3 steps)\n  - P8: Spark-discharge to glycine then aldol/beta-hydroxy route (2 steps)\n  - P9: Hydrothermal acetaldehyde plus glycine aldol route (4 steps)\n  - P10: Sugar-derived threose branch to threonine (4 steps)\n\nHUB MOLECULES: mol_004, mol_005, mol_007, mol_009, mol_012\nCONVERGENCE POINTS: 4\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH ON TARGET MOLECULE ===\nThe following research was conducted on the target molecule before network generation. Use it to assess whether the network aligns with known prebiotic chemistry literature.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n# Prebiotic Synthesis Report: Threonine\n\n## 1. Executive summary\nThis report is restricted to validated/analysed workspace content from the available s5/s6 upstream artifacts and their cited source lists. No uncited claims are introduced.\n\nAcross the retained threonine network, the strongest **direct positive experimental support** for abiotic threonine formation is the **aminomalononitrile (AMN) + electrophile(s) + hydrolysis** route, for which t