\n        \"Mark rxn_002 and rxn_003 as speculative if retained\",\n        \"Keep hydrothermal chemistry as upstream reduced-carbon supply rather than a detailed threonine-specific feeder route\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.42,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.72,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.83\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.66,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.79,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.82,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.87,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.74,\n      \"feedback\": \"This pathway corresponds to the literature-acknowledged but under-demonstrated 2-hydroxybutanal Strecker branch. Strecker conversion of a suitable hydroxy aldehyde to threonine aminonitrile and then hydrolysis is chemically plausible. However, the generation of 2-hydroxybutanal from acetaldehyde/formaldehyde via a generic beta-hydroxy aldehyde pool is not convincingly specified, and the report explicitly notes the lack of direct threonine-specific experimental validation for this route.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_007\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Provide a more explicit and literature-grounded route to 2-hydroxybutanal\",\n        \"Label the entire branch as hypothesis-supported rather than experimentally established\",\n        \"Preserve mixed threonine/allothreonine output rather than implying selectivity\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.74,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.5,\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.38,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.42,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.72,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.83\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.58,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.7,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.84,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.85,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.68,\n      \"feedback\": \"This pathway compounds the weaknesses of the speculative hydrothermal carbonyl-generation branch and the under-demonstrated 2-hydroxybutanal Strecker branch. Although the overall route reaches the target and respects environmental staging, too many steps are weakly grounded in the supplied threonine literature to justify high confidence.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_002\",\n        \"rxn_003\",\n        \"rxn_007\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Shorten the route by using experimentally supported surface precursors rather than speculative hydrothermal carbonyl elaboration\",\n        \"Reduce dependence on rxn_003 and rxn_007\",\n        \"Treat hydrothermal chemistry primarily as a destruction constraint and general feedstock context\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.42,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.72,\n        \"rxn_015\": 0.79,\n        \"rxn_014\": 0.84\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.69,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.82,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.8,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.89,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.76,\n      \"feedback\": \"The amide-hydrolysis sequence is chemically sensible and improves mechanistic realism relative to a one-step nitrile-to-amino-acid conversion. However, the front end still depends on the weakly supported 2-hydroxybutanal branch. The hydrolysis sequence itself is plausible, but the literature supplied does not strongly document threonine amide as an observed prebiotic intermediate.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_007\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Retain the amide sequence as a mechanistic elaboration but note it as inferred\",\n        \"Strengthen or replace the route to 2-hydroxybutanal\",\n        \"Separate experimentally supported and speculative portions more clearly\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.76\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.77,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.86,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.72,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.85,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.8,\n      \"feedback\": \"This pathway aligns with the second major literature-supported source of threonine/allothreonine: spark-discharge chemistry. Its main issue is that the represented inputs do not match the reported canonical discharge gas mixtures in the literature, which emphasize CH4, N2, H2O, NH3 and variants, whereas the network uses formaldehyde, ammonia, and water to generate a mixed pool plus direct threonine. As a compressed representation of a discharge precursor pool, it is acceptable but chemically oversimplified.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_011\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Use a more literature-faithful discharge feed gas set for the spark route\",\n        \"Separate discharge pool formation from aqueous hydrolysis and product analysis\",\n        \"Avoid implying formaldehyde is the direct sole precursor in the discharge experiment\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.76,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.82,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.88\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.81,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.87,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.8,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.91,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.84,\n      \"feedback\": \"This is a reasonable hybrid pathway linking spark-generated cyanide-rich precursor chemistry to the better-supported AMN route. The conceptual flow is literature-consistent, but the implementation compresses several distinct steps and leaves the origin of AMN from the spark pool under-specified. Still, it is more defensible than purely speculative carbonyl elaboration branches.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_011\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Add an explicit step or justification connecting discharge-derived HCN chemistry to AMN formation\",\n        \"Clarify whether AMN is formed in situ or concentrated post-discharge\",\n        \"Keep direct and indirect spark roles distinct\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.76,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.56\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.63,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.73,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.78,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.8,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.69,\n      \"feedback\": \"The spark-to-glycine part is reasonable in broad Miller-Urey context, but the glycine plus acetaldehyde beta-hydroxy route to threonine is only weakly supported in the supplied literature. The network also conflates a probable intermediate 2-amino-3-oxobutanoic acid with direct product formation, making the chemistry appear more established than it is.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_012\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Treat the glycine-acetaldehyde route as speculative and reduce confidence accordingly\",\n        \"Specify whether mineral or pH assistance is merely contextual rather than experimentally validated\",\n        \"Avoid direct one-step conversion to threonine unless supported by explicit literature\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.74,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.5,\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.38,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.56\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.52,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.66,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.82,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.79,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.61,\n      \"feedback\": \"This pathway is significantly weakened by two issues: speculative hydrothermal production of acetaldehyde from CO2/H2-derived intermediates, and weak literature support for the glycine plus acetaldehyde route to threonine. It is connected and conceptually plausible in a broad sense, but not well supported by the provided evidence.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_002\",\n        \"rxn_003\",\n        \"rxn_012\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Remove or replace the hydrothermal acetaldehyde feeder steps\",\n        \"Recast the aldol branch as exploratory rather than a core target-producing route\",\n        \"Prefer the AMN and spark-discharge branches as primary routes\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.74,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.5,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.68,\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.4\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.56,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.67,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.84,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.74,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.62,\n      \"feedback\": \"The precursor-level literature support for threose formation exists, but the conversion from threose to threonine is not directly demonstrated in the retained evidence. The pathway is therefore more of an inferred conceptual branch than an experimentally grounded route. The formaldehyde-to-threose step is broadly plausible under formose chemistry, but the terminal sugar-derived beta-hydroxy conversion is weakly specified.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_013\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Present this branch explicitly as precursor-level speculation\",\n        \"Do not treat threose-derived threonine formation as validated\",\n        \"If retained, add mechanistic detail for amination/redox sequence or lower confidence further\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"best_pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n  \"overall_confidence\": 0.78,\n  \"